WEBVTT

00:37.788 --> 00:39.528
In my 22 years as a judge,

00:39.665 --> 00:44.785
l have often felt obligated,
out of love and loyalty to New Orleans,

00:44.921 --> 00:49.585
to defend my city from those outsiders
who like to speak ill about it.

00:49.717 --> 00:51.799
Too many are quick to describe this city

00:51.928 --> 00:55.671
as a bastion of corruption,
of bureaucratic incompetence,

00:55.806 --> 00:58.934
of Southern laziness, of ineffectual policing

00:59.060 --> 01:02.427
and systemic dysfunction
within our legal system.

01:03.272 --> 01:06.059
No, I try to argue, the city is not that bad.

01:06.192 --> 01:09.309
Our reputation is grossly overblown.

01:09.445 --> 01:11.731
Yet here I sit

01:11.864 --> 01:15.231
with evidence indicating
that the Orleans Parish Prison

01:15.368 --> 01:18.360
had custody of a young man for six months,

01:18.496 --> 01:22.614
and during that same period,
denied this simple fact.

01:22.750 --> 01:24.206
Your Honor,

01:24.335 --> 01:26.747
records necessary to indicate
whether or not...

01:26.879 --> 01:30.337
I know, I know. They were undenNater
or the jail was flooded.

01:30.466 --> 01:32.206
That will be your line of argument.

01:32.343 --> 01:35.050
No doubt you will lean hard on it,
Miss Dufossat.

01:35.179 --> 01:38.467
But knowing that this young man
has been lost in the system,

01:38.599 --> 01:41.841
that many of our public figures
would rather he stay lost

01:41.978 --> 01:44.765
than to admit the obvious -
that there were fundamental problems

01:44.897 --> 01:49.641
with how ourjail inmates were handled
during the storm and its aftermath -

01:49.777 --> 01:54.020
I cannot put into words
the embarrassment | feel for us all.

01:56.701 --> 02:00.944
Ma'am, allow me to apologize
to you and your family

02:01.080 --> 02:04.868
on behalf of Orleans Parish
and the State of Louisiana.

02:05.001 --> 02:09.665
My sincerest regret for what
we have put your family through.

02:13.801 --> 02:17.510
Now, the Criminal Sheriff of Orleans Parish

02:17.638 --> 02:22.382
and the Louisiana State
Department of Corrections have 72 hours

02:22.518 --> 02:27.057
to produce this young man,
or be held in contempt of this court.

02:27.189 --> 02:29.316
That's it. We're recessed.

02:29.442 --> 02:31.854
— (Gavel bangs)
— (Bailiff) All rise.

04:27.101 --> 04:29.308
George, that wasn't here last time.

04:29.437 --> 04:31.143
Don't let that stop us.

04:47.121 --> 04:51.114
Now once I'm set up in there,
you call the TV station,

04:51.250 --> 04:53.241
— let 'em know.
— Police too?

04:53.377 --> 04:56.915
— The reporters first and then the police.
— OK.

04:58.340 --> 05:00.205
(Creaking, clattering)

05:10.978 --> 05:14.311
Hm. Look at this.

05:14.440 --> 05:16.977
What'd | tell you?

05:17.109 --> 05:20.397
Some of the best—constructed
buildings in the city.

05:20.529 --> 05:24.613
Hm. A little bit of mold and dust.

05:24.742 --> 05:26.482
But othenNise...

05:28.662 --> 05:30.368
You sure your mama's all right with this, Ronnie?

05:30.498 --> 05:32.284
No, she don't mind. As a matter of fact,

05:35.169 --> 05:36.750
What else you gonna need, Chief?

05:36.879 --> 05:38.835
I'm gonna need a new bolt lock on that door.

05:38.964 --> 05:40.249
You got it.

05:40.382 --> 05:42.634
You can call me if you need
something to eat, Chief.

05:42.760 --> 05:44.466
Mm—hm.

05:44.595 --> 05:46.711
My niece left that.

05:46.847 --> 05:50.385
"Times are not good here."

05:50.518 --> 05:52.054
Sound familiar?

05:52.186 --> 05:54.848
1880, remember.

05:54.980 --> 05:57.141
"The city is crumbling into ashes.

05:57.274 --> 05:59.890
"It has been buried
under a lava flood of taxes

06:00.027 --> 06:03.645
"and frauds and maladministrations."

06:03.781 --> 06:05.442
Well...

06:05.574 --> 06:07.735
The more things change...

06:07.868 --> 06:08.983
(Chuckling)

06:09.119 --> 06:10.859
"lts condition is so bad

06:10.996 --> 06:14.488
"that when | write about it,
nobody will believe I'm telling the truth."

06:14.625 --> 06:16.411
And here's the kicker.

06:16.544 --> 06:18.660
"But it is better to live here

06:18.796 --> 06:21.333
"in sackcloth and ashes

06:21.465 --> 06:24.332
"than it is to own the whole state of Ohio."

06:24.468 --> 06:26.550
(Students chuckling)

06:26.679 --> 06:30.012
Some of you are doubtless from Ohio.
You know what he's talking about.

06:31.350 --> 06:34.387
Lafcadio Hearn was not the first man
to fall in love with New Orleans.

06:34.520 --> 06:37.182
Certainly he wasn't the last.

06:37.314 --> 06:39.600
lts frauds and farces

06:39.733 --> 06:44.022
represent some of America's
worst excesses and affronts.

06:45.281 --> 06:47.567
But...

06:47.700 --> 06:49.236
day by day,

06:49.368 --> 06:51.359
year by year,

06:51.495 --> 06:56.455
New Orleans also conjures
moments of artistic clarity

06:56.584 --> 06:57.949
and urban transcendence

06:58.085 --> 07:02.124
that are the best that Americans
as a people can hope for.

07:03.966 --> 07:07.049
That is if we who bear witness to them

07:07.177 --> 07:11.386
are not too jaded, too spent

07:11.515 --> 07:15.758
and too stupid to recognize them

07:15.894 --> 07:17.885
for what they are.

